================================================================================
REVIEWED SUMMARY (reviewed — unverified items marked NOT VERIFIED)
================================================================================

C++ emAvlTreeSet.h: copy-on-write sorted set backed by emAvlTree.

Zero emCore consumers. 4 files outside emCore use this type.
Gap will surface when emOsm or emStocks are ported.

C++ provides:
  Sorted set with ordered access (GetFirst, GetLast, GetNearest*),
  set algebra operators (&=, |=, -=, +=), COW copy semantics,
  and stable iterators that survive mutations.

Closest Rust stdlib equivalent: BTreeSet
  - Contains, Insert, Remove, Clear, IsEmpty, GetCount -> direct equivalents
  - GetFirst/GetLast -> .first() / .last() (nightly) or .iter().next() / .iter().next_back()
  - GetNearest* -> .range() with Bound
  - Set algebra -> BitAnd, BitOr, Sub traits on &BTreeSet (return new sets)
    C++ &=, |=, -= mutate in place. Rust equivalents are .retain() and
    .extend(), not operator overloads.

No Rust equivalent exists for:
  COW copy semantics — BTreeSet always deep copies on .clone().
  Stable iterators — BTreeSet iterators borrow immutably.
  GetWritable — COW mutation trigger. BTreeSet elements are not
    directly mutable (must remove and re-insert).
  GetDataRefCount / MakeNonShared — COW refcount management.

NOT VERIFIED: how the 4 outside-emCore files use emAvlTreeSet.
  Whether they depend on COW, stable iterators, ordered access,
  or set algebra is not checked.
